'''Uterine hyperstimulation''' or '''hypertonic uterine dysfunction''' is a potential [[Complication (medicine)|complication]] of [[induction (birth)|labor induction]].  It is defined as either a series of single contractions lasting 2 minutes or more OR a contraction frequency of five or more in 10 minutes.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Briggs GG, Wan SR |title=Drug therapy during labor and delivery, part 2 |journal=Am J Health Syst Pharm |volume=63 |issue=12 |pages=1131–9 |date=June 2006 |pmid=16754739 |doi=10.2146/ajhp050265.p2 |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/535774 |accessdate=2009-08-03}}, which cites:
:{{cite journal |author=American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists |authorlink=American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists |title = Induction of labor | journal = ACOG practice Bulletin |volume=10 |location=Washington, DC |date=December 1999}}</ref>  Uterine hyperstimulation may result in [[fetal distress|fetal heart rate abnormalities]], [[uterine rupture]], or [[placental abruption]].  It is usually treated by administering [[terbutaline]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Briggs GG, Wan SR |title=Drug therapy during labor and delivery, part 2 |journal=Am J Health Syst Pharm |volume=63 |issue=12 |pages=1131–9 |date=June 2006 |pmid=16754739 |doi=10.2146/ajhp050265.p2 |url=http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/535774 |accessdate=2009-08-03}}</ref>

